       =20





  <section>

   =20

   =20
     =20
       =20
         =20



    <p data-block-key=3D"y7ti9"><b>A period is the part of the&nbsp;menstru=
al cycle when a woman bleeds from her vagina for a few days.</b></p><p data=
-block-key=3D"fgooe">For most women this happens around every 28 days, but =
it's common for periods to be more or less frequent than this, ranging from=
 every 21 days to every 35 days.</p><p data-block-key=3D"8l1qe">Your period=
&nbsp;can last between&nbsp;2 and 7&nbsp;days, but it will usually last for=
 about 5 days. The bleeding tends to be heaviest in the first 2 days.</p><p=
 data-block-key=3D"jakt1">When your period is at its heaviest, the blood wi=
ll be red. On lighter days, it may be pink or brown.</p><p data-block-key=
=3D"mbaak">You'll lose about 20 to 90ml (about 1 to 5 tablespoons) of blood=
 during your period,&nbsp;although some women bleed more heavily than this.=
</p><p data-block-key=3D"tv3tw">Read more about&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://www=
.nhs.uk/conditions/heavy-periods/">heavy periods</a>, <a href=3D"https://ww=
w.nhs.uk/symptoms/period-pain/">period pain</a>, <a href=3D"https://www.nhs=
.uk/symptoms/irregular-periods/">irregular periods</a>&nbsp;and <a href=3D"=
https://www.nhs.uk/symptoms/missed-or-late-periods/">stopped or missed peri=
ods</a>.</p>

       =20
     =20
   =20
  </section>






  <section>

   =20
   =20
      <h2>When do periods start?</h2>
   =20

   =20
     =20
       =20
         =20



    <p data-block-key=3D"tcdgh">Periods usually begin at around the age of&=
nbsp;12, although some girls will start them earlier or later.</p><p data-b=
lock-key=3D"mssb4">A delay in&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://www.nhs.uk/conditions=
/periods/starting-periods/">starting periods</a> isn't usually a cause for =
concern. Most girls will be having regular periods&nbsp;by age&nbsp;16 to 1=
8.</p><p data-block-key=3D"96229">Read more about <a href=3D"https://www.nh=
s.uk/conditions/early-or-delayed-puberty/">early or delayed puberty</a>.</p=
>

       =20
     =20
   =20
  </section>






  <section>

   =20
   =20
      <h2>Period products</h2>
   =20

   =20
     =20
       =20
         =20



    <p data-block-key=3D"an819">Period products&nbsp;soak up or collect the=
 blood released during your period. The main types of period products are:<=
/p><ul><li data-block-key=3D"4uhr4">pads</li><li data-block-key=3D"fm3qo">t=
ampons</li><li data-block-key=3D"uj0me">menstrual cups</li></ul><h3 data-bl=
ock-key=3D"ro6wl">Pads</h3><p data-block-key=3D"i2x9b">Pads are strips of p=
adding that have a sticky side you attach to your underwear to hold them in=
 place. One side of the pad is made of an absorbent material&nbsp;that soak=
s up the blood.</p><p data-block-key=3D"yfrst">Pads come in many sizes, so =
you can choose one to suit how heavy or light your period is.</p><p data-bl=
ock-key=3D"1ushr">You can also get reusable washable pads.</p><p data-block=
-key=3D"o11wz">Pantyliners are a smaller and thinner type of pad that can b=
e used on days when your period is very light.</p><h3 data-block-key=3D"kop=
oh">Tampons</h3><p data-block-key=3D"nefuq">Tampons are small tubes of cott=
on wool that you insert into your vagina to soak up the blood before it com=
es out of your body.</p><p data-block-key=3D"yxyda">There are 2 types of ta=
mpon =E2=80=93 ones that come with an applicator and others without an appl=
icator that you insert with your fingers. In both cases, there's a string a=
t one end of the tampon, which you pull to remove it.</p><p data-block-key=
=3D"z24ex">Tampons come with instructions that explain how to use them. If =
the tampon is inserted correctly, you should not be able to feel it inside =
you. If you can feel it or it hurts, it might not be in properly.</p><p dat=
a-block-key=3D"y7e6i">It is not possible for a tampon to get lost inside yo=
u. Your vagina holds it firmly in place and it expands inside you as it soa=
ks up the blood.</p><h3 data-block-key=3D"dgmhb">Menstrual cups</h3><p data=
-block-key=3D"n0ma9">Menstrual cups are an alternative to pads and tampons.=
 The cup is made from silicone and you put it inside your vagina.</p><p dat=
a-block-key=3D"0bnan">Menstrual cups collect the blood rather than absorb i=
t. Unlike tampons and most pads, which are thrown away after they've been u=
sed, you can wash menstrual cups and use them again.</p><h3 data-block-key=
=3D"454mu">Period underwear</h3><p data-block-key=3D"2v67h">Period underwea=
r are pants made from absorbent fabric. They soak up blood in the same way =
as pads, and have a layer to prevent leaks. They're designed to be washed a=
nd reused.</p>

       =20
     =20
   =20
  </section>






  <section>

   =20
   =20
      <h2>PMS (premenstrual syndrome)</h2>
   =20

   =20
     =20
       =20
         =20



    <p data-block-key=3D"jitkl">Changes in your body's hormone&nbsp;levels =
before your period can cause physical and emotional changes.</p><p data-blo=
ck-key=3D"v9w6v">This is known as <a href=3D"https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/=
pre-menstrual-syndrome/">PMS (premenstrual syndrome)</a> or PMT (premenstru=
al tension).</p><p data-block-key=3D"re7pe">There are many possible symptom=
s of PMS, but typical symptoms include:</p><ul><li data-block-key=3D"po9k7"=
>feeling bloated</li><li data-block-key=3D"ijht2">breast tenderness</li><li=
 data-block-key=3D"q4v5e">mood swings</li><li data-block-key=3D"x1hrb">feel=
ing irritable</li><li data-block-key=3D"585t2">spotty skin</li><li data-blo=
ck-key=3D"jwn5v"><a href=3D"https://www.nhs.uk/symptoms/loss-of-libido/">lo=
w sex drive (loss of libido)</a></li><li data-block-key=3D"7l0fa">headaches=
</li></ul><p data-block-key=3D"2pjn9">These symptoms usually improve when y=
our period starts and disappear a few days afterwards. Not all women who ha=
ve periods get PMS.</p>

       =20
     =20
   =20
  </section>






  <section>

   =20
   =20
      <h2>Getting pregnant</h2>
   =20

   =20
     =20
       =20
         =20



    <p data-block-key=3D"nsg94">Working out&nbsp;when you can get pregnant&=
nbsp;=E2=80=93&nbsp;your fertile time&nbsp;=E2=80=93&nbsp;can be difficult.=
 It's around the time you ovulate, which is about 12 to 16 days before the =
start of your next period.</p><p data-block-key=3D"1gskt">But sperm can sur=
vive inside a woman's body for up to 7 days before ovulation occurs. This m=
eans your fertile time extends back earlier in your&nbsp;cycle.</p><p data-=
block-key=3D"vsuru">You can calculate when your period will start and your =
peak ovulation times using an online period calendar.</p><p data-block-key=
=3D"gbihe">You cannot get pregnant if you do not ovulate. Some hormonal met=
hods of contraception, such as the <a href=3D"https://www.nhs.uk/contracept=
ion/methods-of-contraception/combined-pill/">combined contraceptive pill</a=
>, <a href=3D"https://www.nhs.uk/contraception/methods-of-contraception/con=
traceptive-patch/">contraceptive patch</a>&nbsp;and <a href=3D"https://www.=
nhs.uk/contraception/methods-of-contraception/contraceptive-injection/">con=
traceptive injection</a>, work by preventing ovulation.</p><p data-block-ke=
y=3D"6szh7">Read more about <a href=3D"https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/period=
s/fertility-in-the-menstrual-cycle/">periods and fertility in the menstrual=
 cycle</a>,&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/infertility/">inf=
ertility</a>,&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://www.nhs.uk/contraception/">contracept=
ion</a>&nbsp;and <a href=3D"https://www.nhs.uk/pregnancy/trying-for-a-baby/=
trying-to-get-pregnant/">trying to get pregnant</a>.</p>

       =20
     =20
   =20
  </section>






  <section>

   =20
   =20
      <h2>Changes in your periods</h2>
   =20

   =20
     =20
       =20
         =20



    <p data-block-key=3D"jc5h1">Your periods can change&nbsp;=E2=80=93 for =
example,&nbsp;they may last longer or get lighter. This does not necessaril=
y mean there's a problem, but it does need to be investigated.</p><p data-b=
lock-key=3D"qu2ys">You can see your&nbsp;GP,&nbsp;or visit your nearest wom=
en's clinic or <a href=3D"https://www.nhs.uk/nhs-services/sexual-health-ser=
vices/find-contraception-services/">contraceptive clinic</a>.</p><p data-bl=
ock-key=3D"udswo"><a href=3D"https://www.nhs.uk/common-health-questions/sex=
ual-health/what-causes-bleeding-between-periods/">Bleeding between periods<=
/a>, bleeding after having sex, or&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://www.nhs.uk/sympt=
oms/post-menopausal-bleeding/">bleeding after the menopause</a> needs to be=
 checked by a doctor.</p><p data-block-key=3D"0ae4c">It might be&nbsp;cause=
d by an infection, abnormalities in the neck of the womb (the cervix)&nbsp;=
or, in rare cases, it could be <a href=3D"https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/can=
cer/">cancer</a>.</p><p data-block-key=3D"dlyqe">You could be pregnant if y=
ou miss a period and you've had sex.&nbsp;See your GP if&nbsp;you've taken =
a&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://www.nhs.uk/pregnancy/trying-for-a-baby/doing-a-pr=
egnancy-test/">pregnancy test</a>&nbsp;and the result is negative (you're n=
ot pregnant) and you've&nbsp;missed 3 consecutive periods.</p><p data-block=
-key=3D"a1cqo">They will investigate the cause and recommend any necessary =
treatment.</p><p data-block-key=3D"jyk6h">Read more about <a href=3D"https:=
//www.nhs.uk/symptoms/missed-or-late-periods/">stopped or missed periods</a=
>.</p>

       =20
     =20
   =20
  </section>






  <section>

   =20
   =20
      <h2>When do periods stop?</h2>
   =20

   =20
     =20
       =20
         =20



    <p data-block-key=3D"8ypvo">Your periods will continue until you reach =
the <a href=3D"https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/menopause/">menopause</a>, whi=
ch usually happens when you are in your&nbsp;mid-40s to mid-50s. In the UK =
the average age of menopause is 51.</p><p data-block-key=3D"s5e0c">Your per=
iods will not usually stop suddenly when you go through the menopause. They=
 may start to become less frequent over a few months or years before stoppi=
ng altogether.</p>

       =20
     =20
   =20
  </section>






  <section>

   =20
   =20
      <h2>Delaying your period</h2>
   =20

   =20
     =20
       =20
         =20



    <p data-block-key=3D"5mr98">It=E2=80=99s possible to delay your period =
if you take the combined contraceptive pill.</p><p data-block-key=3D"9rgco"=
>How you do this depends on the type of combined pill you take. Speak to a =
GP or pharmacist, or a doctor or nurse at a sexual health clinic, about how=
 to delay your period using the combined pill.</p><p data-block-key=3D"a6qo=
u">If you do not take the combined pill already, you will need to start it =
a few weeks before the time you want to delay your period.</p><p data-block=
-key=3D"adpsq">If you do not want to take the contraceptive pill, your GP c=
an prescribe a medicine called norethisterone to delay your periods, but th=
is is not suitable for everyone.</p>

       =20
     =20
   =20
  </section>






